<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,572]" pageId="9" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,295,320]" pageId="9" pageNumber="187">Variability.</emphasis>
Sides of emargination on elytral apex with one or two short spines or regular denticles, variability as in 
<figureCitation box="[210,286,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1805,1828]" captionTargetBox="[240,1316,194,1766]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[228,1360,194,1788]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. The shape of elytral apex. A – C, Coraebus hastanus hastanus; D – F, C. hastanus oberthueri; G – I, C. hastanus ephippiatus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/215920/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="187">
Figs. 
<number box="[272,286,332,356]" pageId="9" pageNumber="187" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
G–I. Colour relatively stable, base of pronotum and elytra always blue or green.
</paragraph>
